{{Other uses2|Korkyra}} In [[Greek mythology]], '''Corcyra''' {{IPAc-en|k|ɔr|ˈ|s|aɪər|ə}} or '''Korkyra''' {{IPAc-en|k|ɔr|ˈ|k|aɪər|ə}}<!--the upsilon is long--> ([[Ancient Greece]]: Κορκυρα) was the daughter of the [[Asopus|Asopos]] river and the [[nymph]] [[Metope (mythology)|Metope]]. According to myth Poseidon fell in love with the beautiful nymph Korkyra, kidnapped her and brought her to a hitherto unnamed island and offered her name to the place: ''Korkyra'' or the now-modern ''Kerkyra'' (known in [[English language|English]] as [[Corfu]], a name that is unrelated by origin<!--Yes, the English name and the Greek name are completely unrelated.-->). Together they had a child [[Phaiax]] after whom the inhabitants of the island, [[Phaiakes]], were named; their name was later transliterated in Latinate orthography to [[Phaeacians]].<ref>[http://www.theoi.com/Text/ApolloniusRhodius4.html Apollonius Rhodius, Argonautica. 4.557]</ref><ref>[http://www.theoi.com/Text/DiodorusSiculus4D.html Diodorus Siculus, Library of History, 4.72.3]</ref>
